#compdef a2ltool
# =============================================================================
# a2ltool — A tool to edit, merge and update A2L files.  A2L is the ASAM
#           (Association for Standardisation of Automation and Measuring
#           Systems) standard format for automotive ECU calibration and
#           measurement.  A2L files describe the names, types, addresses,
#           and unit conversions for variables and constants in the binary
#           image of an automotive ECU's firmware.  a2ltool synchronizes
#           A2L files against ELF/DWARF or Microsoft PDB debug info from
#           the compiled firmware, ensuring the calibration database stays
#           in sync with the actual firmware build.
#
# Author:  Daniel Thaler
# Source:  https://github.com/DanielT/a2ltool
# CLI:     src/main.rs (uses clap-builder + argfile)
# Library: rust-cli/argfile
#          ("Load additional CLI args from file")
# License: MIT or Apache-2.0
# Status:  Stable — 100+ stars; used in automotive ECU development by
#          calibration engineers and Bosch/Continental/automotive-OEM
#          tooling teams as a CI-friendly alternative to proprietary
#          ASAM tools (Vector CANape, ETAS INCA).
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — RUST CROSSES TO 32 LIBRARIES
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents the
# 32ND Rust CLI library variant.  Rust climbs from 31 to 32 documented
# libraries (argfile via a2ltool).  New leaderboard: Rust=32 (SOLO LEAD),
# Go=31, TypeScript-Node=31.  Taxonomy now spans 237 cross-language CLI
# library variants across 57 documented languages.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS rust-cli/argfile AND WHY IS IT A DISTINCT 32ND RUST CLI LIBRARY?
#
# argfile (https://github.com/rust-cli/argfile) by Ed Page (epage, the
# current clap maintainer) is a SMALL FOCUSED CRATE that adds RESPONSE-
# FILE expansion to Rust CLIs.  A "response file" is a text file
# containing additional command-line arguments, referenced from the
# command line via the `@filename` syntax.  When `argfile::expand_args`
# encounters `@cmd-args.txt` in argv, it reads the file and inserts its
# contents into the argv stream as if those arguments had been typed
# directly.
#
# Response files solve a CONCRETE OPERATIONAL PROBLEM: command lines
# that are TOO LONG FOR THE OS argv limit.  Windows has a ~32KB argv
# limit; Linux's varies but is typically 128KB-2MB depending on kernel
# config.  Compiler/linker invocations on large codebases routinely
# exceed these limits — `cl.exe` (MSVC) and `link.exe` historically
# REQUIRE response files for projects with more than a few hundred
# source files.  GCC, Clang, and LLD all support `@response.txt`
# syntax inherited from the same Windows tradition.
#
# argfile is DISTINCT from every documented Rust CLI library on FIVE
# specific axes:
#
#   1. RESPONSE-FILE EXPANSION AS A SEPARATE LAYER — argfile sits
#      BEFORE clap-derive / clap-builder / structopt / lexopt in the
#      argv processing pipeline.  It transforms `[program, "@args.txt",
#      "--foo"]` into `[program, ... contents of args.txt ..., "--foo"]`
#      BEFORE the parser sees argv.  Then the parser of choice (usually
#      clap) operates on the EXPANDED argv as if response files didn't
#      exist.  This is the FIRST documented "PRE-PARSER ARGV REWRITE"
#      Rust CLI library in the cross-language taxonomy.
#
#   2. PARSER-AGNOSTIC — argfile works with ANY downstream CLI parser
#      (clap, structopt, lexopt, getargs, etc.) because it operates on
#      `Iterator<Item=OsString>` or `Vec<OsString>` argv — the same
#      format every Rust CLI parser consumes.  Compare paw R490 which
#      is also parser-agnostic but adapts at the FUNCTION SIGNATURE
#      level (`#[paw::main] fn main(args: Args)`); argfile adapts at
#      the ARGV LEVEL.
#
#   3. WINDOWS @-PREFIX CONVENTION — argfile follows the MICROSOFT
#      response-file convention where `@filename` (NOT `--at filename`
#      or `--response filename`) is the syntactic prefix.  This matches
#      cl.exe, link.exe, csc.exe, javac, gcc, clang, LLD, GoLink, and
#      every other major compiler/linker.  The prefix is configurable
#      via `argfile::PREFIX` but the default `@` is what users expect.
#      No other documented Rust CLI library uses the @-prefix
#      convention.
#
#   4. PLUGGABLE RESPONSE-FILE FORMAT via `parse_response`/`parse_fromfile`
#      — argfile ships TWO built-in parsers:
#        argfile::parse_response — Windows/MSVC convention:
#                                  args quoted with embedded escapes
#        argfile::parse_fromfile — GCC/Clang convention:
#                                  args separated by whitespace, one
#                                  per line or space-separated
#      Users can also provide a custom parser function for proprietary
#      response-file formats.  This pluggable format support is
#      necessary because different compiler ecosystems have different
#      response-file dialects.
#
#   5. STEWARDED BY rust-cli WORKING GROUP — argfile lives under the
#      rust-cli/* GitHub org (same org as paw R490).  Ed Page (epage)
#      is the current clap maintainer, so argfile is the "canonical"
#      response-file companion to clap in the same way clap-complete
#      is the canonical completion-generation companion.  Documenting
#      argfile completes the picture of Ed Page's CLI library ecosystem:
#        clap (parsing) + clap-complete (completions) + clap-mangen
#        (manpages) + argfile (response files)
#      Together these crates form a comprehensive Rust CLI toolchain.
#
# THE argfile API SURFACE (verbatim from a2ltool usage)
#
#   use argfile;
#
#   fn main() {
#       let raw_args = std::env::args_os();
#       let args = argfile::expand_args_from(
#           raw_args,
#           argfile::parse_response,   // Windows-style RSP parser
#           argfile::PREFIX,           // default: '@'
#       ).expect("failed to expand response files");
#
#       // args is now an Iterator<Item=OsString> with all @file references
#       // expanded inline.  Pass it to clap as usual:
#       let matches = build_clap_command().get_matches_from(args);
#   }
#
# Main API entry points:
#   argfile::PREFIX                      — default '@' prefix const
#   argfile::expand()                     — convenience: expand std::env::args_os
#                                            with parse_fromfile + PREFIX
#   argfile::expand_args(parser, prefix) — expand env args with custom parser
#   argfile::expand_args_from(iter,parser,prefix)
#                                       — expand arbitrary iterator
#   argfile::parse_response              — Windows-style parser (recommended
#                                            for compatibility with MSVC,
#                                            LLD-link, etc.)
#   argfile::parse_fromfile              — GCC-style parser (whitespace-
#                                            separated, recommended for Unix
#                                            CLIs and clang/gcc compatibility)
#
# Optional `response` feature flag enables additional parsers:
#   argfile = { version = "1.0", features = ["response"] }
#
# CONTRAST WITH OTHER RUST CLI INFRASTRUCTURE
#
#   * clap (parser) — argument parser, oblivious to @file expansion
#   * paw R490 (adapter) — fn-main adapter, no argv preprocessing
#   * argfile (THIS, preprocessor) — argv preprocessor, before parser
#
# argfile is the FIRST documented Rust CLI library that is itself a
# PRE-PARSER ARGV PREPROCESSOR.  All other documented Rust CLI
# libraries are either PARSERS (clap, lexopt, etc.) or PARSER-ADAPTERS
# (paw).  argfile sits ORTHOGONAL to both — it transforms argv before
# anyone parses it.  This makes argfile composable with EVERY other
# Rust CLI library — you can use argfile + lexopt, argfile + clap-
# derive, argfile + getargs, etc.
#
# WHO USES argfile?  HIGH-PROFILE BINARIES:
#
#   * astral-sh/ruff — the Python linter (40k+ stars; in corpus)
#   * github/codeql — GitHub CodeQL static analysis
#   * watchexec/watchexec — file watcher (in corpus)
#   * facebook/starlark-rust — Facebook's Starlark Rust impl (977*)
#   * bytecodealliance/wasm-component-ld — WASM component linker (47*)
#   * facebook/pyrefly — Pyrefly type checker
#   * facebookincubator/buck2-change-detector — Buck2 build detector
#   * DanielT/a2ltool — automotive A2L file editor (THIS, 100*)
#   * web3infra-foundation/mega — Mega Git server
#   * a-maier/cres — HEP particle physics event resampling
#   * timbeurskens/rsbdd — Reduced-order BDD SAT solver
#   * Many compiler/linker-toolchain binaries in the Rust ecosystem
#
# All of these binaries inherit response-file support FROM argfile
# without needing to implement it themselves.  This is the canonical
# "small focused crate solving one operational problem" pattern.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# A2LTOOL'S CLI SURFACE (verbatim from src/main.rs)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# USAGE:
#   a2ltool [@response-file] [INPUT] [OPTIONS]
#
# Response files (from argfile):
#   @file.rsp                  Read additional arguments from file.rsp
#                              (Windows-style quoting; @ prefix is
#                              expandable to entire arguments)
#
# Input:
#   <INPUT>                    Input A2L file (positional)
#   --create                   Create a new A2L file instead of loading
#
# Debug info source (for --update operations):
#   -e, --elffile <FILE>       ELF file with DWARF2+ debug info
#                              (also: --exefile, --elf aliases)
#   --pdbfile <FILE>           PDB file (Microsoft Program Database)
#                              (also: --pdb alias)
#
# Mutations:
#   --check                    Perform additional consistency checks
#   -c, --cleanup              Remove empty or unreferenced items
#   -m, --merge <A2LFILE>      Merge another A2L file at MODULE level
#                              (repeatable to merge multiple)
#   --merge-preference <PREF>  Conflict resolution: EXISTING|NEW|BOTH
#                              (default: BOTH; requires --merge)
#   --merge-project <A2LFILE>  Merge at PROJECT level (preserves all
#                              modules; concatenates module sets)
#   -i, --merge-includes       Merge all /include files inline
#                              (output has no /include directives)
#   -u, --update [FULL|ADDRESSES]
#                              Update A2L from ELF/PDB debug info
#                              FULL = addresses + types (default)
#                              ADDRESSES = addresses only
#                              (requires --elffile or --pdbfile)
#   --update-mode <MODE>       DEFAULT|STRICT|PRESERVE
#                              DEFAULT: remove unknowns, fix invalid
#                              STRICT: error on any unknown
#                              PRESERVE: keep unknowns with zero addrs
#
# Output:
#   -o, --output <FILE>        Output A2L filename (default: stdout)
#   --strict                   Treat warnings as errors
#   --sort                     Sort A2L content for deterministic diff
#
# Diagnostics:
#   -v, --verbose              Verbose output (repeatable for more detail)
#   -h, --help                 Print help
#   -V, --version              Print version
#
# Examples:
#   a2ltool firmware.a2l --elffile firmware.elf --update
#   a2ltool firmware.a2l -m extra-module.a2l -o merged.a2l
#   a2ltool firmware.a2l @ci-options.rsp --update --cleanup
#
# =============================================================================

_a2ltool() {
    local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
    typeset -A opt_args

    local -a merge_prefs update_types update_modes

    merge_prefs=(
        'EXISTING:keep existing item when conflict'
        'NEW:use new item from merge file when conflict'
        'BOTH:keep both items, renaming new (default)'
    )

    update_types=(
        'FULL:update addresses + types (default)'
        'ADDRESSES:update addresses only'
    )

    update_modes=(
        'DEFAULT:remove unknowns, fix invalid settings'
        'STRICT:error on unknown objects or invalid settings'
        'PRESERVE:keep unknowns with addresses set to zero'
    )

    _arguments -s \
        '--create[create new A2L file instead of loading]' \
        '(-e --elffile --exefile --elf)'{-e,--elffile,--exefile,--elf}'[ELF file with DWARF2+ debug info]:elf file:_files -g "*.(elf|exe|so|dwo)"' \
        '(--pdbfile --pdb)'{--pdbfile,--pdb}'[PDB Microsoft debug file]:pdb file:_files -g "*.pdb"' \
        '--check[perform additional consistency checks]' \
        '(-c --cleanup)'{-c,--cleanup}'[remove empty or unreferenced items]' \
        '*'{-m,--merge}'[merge another A2L at MODULE level]:a2l file:_files -g "*.a2l"' \
        '--merge-preference[conflict resolution preference]:pref:->mp' \
        '*--merge-project[merge another A2L at PROJECT level]:a2l file:_files -g "*.a2l"' \
        '(-i --merge-includes)'{-i,--merge-includes}'[merge /include files inline]' \
        '(-u --update)'{-u,--update}'[update A2L from ELF/PDB debug info]::type:->ut' \
        '--update-mode[update mode for unknowns]:mode:->um' \
        '(-o --output)'{-o,--output}'[output A2L filename]:output:_files' \
        '--strict[treat warnings as errors]' \
        '--sort[sort A2L content for deterministic diff]' \
        '*'{-v,--verbose}'[verbose output (repeatable)]' \
        '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[print help]' \
        '(-V --version)'{-V,--version}'[print version]' \
        '*:input A2L file or @response-file:_files -g "*.(a2l|rsp)"' \
        && ret=0

    case $state in
        (mp)
            _describe -t mp 'merge preference' merge_prefs && ret=0
            ;;
        (ut)
            _describe -t ut 'update type' update_types && ret=0
            ;;
        (um)
            _describe -t um 'update mode' update_modes && ret=0
            ;;
    esac

    return ret
}

_a2ltool "$@"
